Tiddlers of type `x-twikki` are rendered as markdown by the [[$BaseMarkdownPlugin]].

The flavor is CommonMark implemented by [markdown-it 14.2.0](https://github.com/markdown-it/markdown-it) but can be overriden by creating a plugin.

## Custom Renderers
A custom plugin can implement a `render()` function to override the `markdown.render` functionality:
```javascript
function myRenderer(markdown) {
  // Implement your renderer here..
  return MyRenderer.toHtml(text); // must return an HTML string
}
tw.core.markdown = {render: myRenderer};
tw.events.override('markdown.render', myRenderer);
```

If no handler is subscribed — i.e. with zero plugins, or if [[$BaseMarkdownPlugin]] is disabled — the platform falls back to escaped plain text. (`?safemode` does *not* cause this: it skips only extension packages, so the base [[$BaseMarkdownPlugin]] still loads and markdown still renders.)

## Installed Plugins

<<plugins>>

Plugins are tiddlers tagged <<Tag $Plugin>> who, when run (with eval()) return `{meta, init, start}`. Each row above shows the plugin's name, source tiddler, version, package, the platform release it was built for, and a compatibility status. [Plugins Docs](https://github.com/cawoodm/twikki/blob/main/docs/PLUGINS.md)

- **✓ OK** — built for this platform release (caret-compatible).
- **⚠ …** — minor mismatch: same major, different minor/patch. The plugin still runs.
- **✗ …** — major mismatch. The plugin still runs but may break — consider updating or removing it.
- **–** — no `platform` field declared (exempt).
- **⚠ err: …** — the plugin's `load`, `init`, or `start` phase threw. Other plugins are unaffected.

Unlike core modules, the plugin gate is **soft**: an incompatible plugin still runs, the table just surfaces the mismatch so you can decide.

## Plugins vs. Scripts

There are two ways for a tiddler to run code at boot:

- <<Tag $Plugin>> — structured plugin with a lifecycle. Its IIFE returns `{meta, init?, start?}` and the platform calls the lifecycle hooks.
- <<Tag $Script>> — code that just runs at boot. No return value, no lifecycle. Use for macros, commands, event subscriptions, one-shot setup.

Tiddlers without either tag never auto-execute.

## Authoring a plugin

```js
// tags: $Plugin
(function () {
  return {
    meta: {name: 'MyPlugin', version: '1.0.0', platform: '0.27.0'},
    init() {
      // event subscriptions, registerMacro/registerCommand, dependency checks
    },
    start() {
      // optional — boot-time effects
    },
  };
})();
```

## Formats

Inswide Twikki a plugin can be a single `script/js` tiddler or a multi-part `x-twikki` tiddler (see [[ContentSections]]. The multi-part option is nice because you can include documentation, examples, stylesheets. See [[ExamplePlugin]] for a multi-part example. As a developer you can manage plugins as individual files in a directory which are automatically compiled into multi-part tiddlers. See the [full developer reference](https://github.com/cawoodm/twikki/blob/main/docs/PLUGINS.md).

## Distributing plugins

A plugin (or script) is shared like any other tiddler — inside a package (a JSON list of tiddlers). Packages are loaded from the URLs listed in [[$CorePackages]] and [[$ExtensionPackages]], or imported on demand with the `<<packages.import>>` widget:

- <<packages.import name:demo url:packages/demo.json filter:\* force:false>>

tw.events.subscribe(
  'ui.loaded',
  () => {
    // Show 'Welcome' if no tiddlers are defined
    let t = tw.run.getTiddler('Welcome');
    if (!t) return;
    if (!tw.tiddlers.visible.length) tw.run.showTiddler('Welcome');
  },
  'website',
);
